        <title>Entry Manifolds</title>
        <paragraph>The sedimentary water enters the sand bed on four levels. Each inlet has a manifold that distributes the water in that layer. The assembly consists of a trunk that is installed in the center of the filter with two “wings” of perforated pipes of smaller diameter (<number_reference internal="True" refid="figure-entry-manifold" title="Fig. %s"><inline classes="std std-numref">Fig. 41</inline></number_reference>).</paragraph>
        <target refid="figure-entry-manifold"></target>
        <figure align="center" ids="id1 figure-entry-manifold" names="figure_entry_manifold">
            <image candidates="{'*': 'Filtration\\Images/entry_manifold.png'}" uri="Filtration\Images/entry_manifold.png" width="500px"></image>
            <caption>The manifold consists of a trunk with two “wings” of perforated pipes. There are tubes of <problematic ids="id3" refid="id2">|ND.FiBranchHolder|</problematic> that receive the perforated tubes on the sides of the box.</caption>
        </figure>
        <paragraph>The objectives in the design of the entry manifolds are:</paragraph>
        <block_quote>
            <enumerated_list enumtype="arabic" prefix="" suffix=".">
                <list_item>
                    <paragraph>Achieve an even distribution of water in the sand layer.</paragraph>
                </list_item>
                <list_item>
                    <paragraph>Prevent sand from entering the tubes.</paragraph>
                </list_item>
                <list_item>
                    <paragraph>Facilitate their manufacture and installation.</paragraph>
                </list_item>
            </enumerated_list>
        </block_quote>
        <paragraph>A restriction on flow distribution throughout the sand bed governs the estimation of the collective area of the holes in the entry manifolds (see <reference internal="True" refuri="Fluid_Distribution#title-distribucion-del-flujo"><inline classes="std std-ref">Flow Distribution</inline></reference>):</paragraph>
        <target refid="equation-flow-restriction"></target>
        <math_block docname="Filtration/Entry_Manifolds" ids="equation-flow-restriction" label="flow_restriction" nowrap="False" number="1" xml:space="preserve">A_{Est}=\frac{Q_{Fi}}{\Pi_{VC}\sqrt{2g\frac{{PR}_{Re}}{\left(1-{\Pi_Q}^2\right)}}}</math_block>
        <line_block>
            <line>Where</line>
            <line><math>A_{Est}</math> = the estimated collective area of the orifices in the backwash manifold = <problematic ids="id5" refid="id4">|A.FiBwManOrificesEst|</problematic></line>
            <line><math>Q _{Fi}</math> = the flow rate per filter = <problematic ids="id7" refid="id6">|Q.Fi|</problematic></line>
            <line><math>\Pi _{VC}</math> = the coefficient of vein contracted for a hole = <problematic ids="id9" refid="id8">|Pi.VCOrifice|</problematic></line>
            <line><math>{PR}_{Re}</math> = the total pressure recovery in the backwash manifold = <problematic ids="id11" refid="id10">|PR.FiBwManTotal|</problematic></line>
            <line><math>\Pi _Q</math> = the minimum radius of the flow on the long path over the flow on the short path = <problematic ids="id13" refid="id12">|Pi.FiManifoldQ|</problematic></line>
        </line_block>
        <paragraph>With this estimation of the collective area, the diameter of the orifices can be defined taking into account the sizes of the commonly available drills:</paragraph>
        <target refid="equation-diameter-bits"></target>
        <math_block docname="Filtration/Entry_Manifolds" ids="equation-diameter-bits" label="diameter_bits" nowrap="False" number="2" xml:space="preserve">D_{Orificio} = CeilNearest\left(\sqrt{\frac{4}{\pi}\frac{A_{Est}}{{L_{Ramal}}/{S_{Orificio}}}},D_{Broca}\right)</math_block>
        <line_block>
            <line>Where</line>
            <line><math>CeilNearest\left(x,M\right)</math> = a function for the value in the matrix <math>M</math> that is closer and larger than the target <math>x</math></line>
            <line><math>L_{Ramal}</math> = the useful length of the branch (depends on the diameter of the manifold stem)</line>
            <line><math>S_{Orifice}</math> = the estimated separation between the orifices = <problematic ids="id15" refid="id14">|B.FiManOrificeEst|</problematic></line>
            <line><math>D_{Drill}</math> = the matrix of commonly available drill diameters</line>
        </line_block>
        <paragraph>The entry manifolds in the middle of the filter bring twice as much water as the lower one because they deliver water to two layers of the filter, so this calculation is repeated independently for the holes in these manifolds with twice this area. The upper intake manifold has the same collective area as the lower manifold because it only delivers water to the upper sand layer. Once the diameter and number of orifices per string and per manifold have been defined, the true collective area of the holes and the true pressure drop through them during normal filtration can be recalculated:</paragraph>
        <target refid="equation-headloss-end"></target>
        <math_block docname="Filtration/Entry_Manifolds" ids="equation-headloss-end" label="headloss_end" nowrap="False" number="3" xml:space="preserve">{HL}_{Orificio}=\frac{\left(\frac{Q_{Capa}}{A_{Capa}\Pi_{VC}\varepsilon_{Arena}}\right)^2}{2g}</math_block>
